The genus 

Tabernaemontana
(Apocynaceae)

has a broad distribution over the tropical and subtropical regions of the world, encompassing parts of America, Africa including 
Madagascar
, Asia, Oceania, and 
Australia
(

). Plants of this genus are used in Chinese, Ayurvedic and Thai traditional medicine for the treatment of dysentery, fever, and pain, as well as for the treatment of snakebites in 
Brazil
(

; 

). Previous studies on the chemical constituents of this genus have resulted in the discovery of many new alkaloids, particularly indole and bisindole alkaloids possessing structurally novel skeletons and useful biological activities (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

, 

; 

, 

; 

). 

Tabernaemontana polyneura
(King & Gamble) D.J. Middleton

(basionym: 

Ervatamia polyneura

) is endemic in Peninsular 
Malaysia
(

). A preliminary phytochemical investigation of 

T. polyneura

(sample collected at Genting Sempah, 
Selangor
, Peninsular 
Malaysia
) was first reported by Clivio et al., in 1990. Since no further studies of this plant have been reported and in view of our interest in probing the variation of alkaloid content as a function of geographical location in this genus, we initiated a larger scale study of a sample collected in a different location (Fraser’ s Hill, 
Pahang
, Peninsular 
Malaysia
), and herein report the results of the isolated compounds (
Fig. 1
).

A search of the literature revealed that a compound similar to 1 was obtained as a by-product during a total synthesis of vinblastine (
). Compound 1 has similar 1 H and 13 C NMR, MS, and IR spectroscopic data compared to those of the synthetic compound ( 10 ) but showed opposite sign for the specific rotation ([α] D 25 44 for
1 vs
[α] D 22 +33 for 10 ), suggesting an enantiomeric relationship between 1 and 10 . In any case, the absolute configuration of 1 was further confirmed by TDDFT-ECD method. The experimental ECD spectrum of 1 showed high-amplitude negative Cotton effects at 220 and 245 nm and positive Cotton effects at 233 and 288 nm , which resemble the calculated ECD spectrum of 1 ( Fig. 4 ), leading to the assignment of the absolute configuration of 1 as (14 S , 16 S , 20 R , 21 R ). In addition, the experimental ECD data also matches with the experimental ECD data of voacangalactone ( 11 ), a 10-methoxy derivative of 1 (
) and this provided further confirmation of the structure and absolute configuration of 1 . A plausible biosynthetic pathway to 1 from an iboga precursor, heyneanine ( 12 ), is shown in Fig. 5 . Generation of a secondary carbocation at C-19 followed by a 1,2-H shift provides a tertiary carbocation at C-20, which on nucleophilic attack by a water molecule leads to 13 . A subsequent intramolecular transesterification furnishes compound 1 .

Polyneurine C ( 3 ) was isolated as a light yellowish oil, [α] D 25 28 ( c 0.2, CHCl 3 ). The UV spectrum showed absorption maxima at 223 and 286 nm , indicating the presence of an indole chromophore, while the IR spectrum showed absorption bands at 3374 and 1726 cm 1 , suggesting the presence of OH/NH and ester carbonyl functions, respectively. The HRESIMS data showed an [M + H] + peak at m/z 385.2130, corresponding to the molecular formula, C 22 H 28 N 2 O 4 . The 1 H NMR data ( Table 1 ) showed the presence of an indolic NH ( δ H 7.89), four aromatic resonances of an unsubstituted indole moiety ( δ H 7.10–7.47), a methyl ester ( δ H 3.72), and a hydroxyethyl side chain ( δ H 1.27, d, J = 6.4 Hz, Me-18; δ H 3.88, qd, J =6.4, 3.2 Hz, H-19). The 13 C NMR data ( Table 2 ) showed the presence of one methyl, five methylenes, nine methines, one methyl ester, one ester carbonyl, two tertiary carbons bonded to indolic NH, and three quaternary carbons, for a total of 22 carbon resonances. The 1 H and 13 C NMR data of 3 showed features typical of iboga alkaloids with some differences, viz., the presence of a hydroxymethyl linked to C-3 and a hydroxyethyl side chain attached to C-20. These observations were supported by the presence of the corresponding oxymethylene (C-3) and oxymethine resonances (C-19), at δ C 60.5 and 70.8, respectively. These assignments were also supported by the HMBC data which showed three-bond correlations from H-24 to C-14, H-15 and H-21 to C-19, and H-18 to C-20 ( Fig. 2 ). The relative configuration was determined via analysis of the NOE data ( Fig. 3 ) as well as from analysis of the vicinal coupling constants ( Table 1 ). The configuration at C-3 was determined to be S based on the NOEs observed between H-3 and H-5 β , H-6 β , H-17 β as well as between H-24 and H-15 β ( Fig. 3 ). The β -orientation of the hydroxyethyl side chain at C-20 was determined based on the H-15 α /H-20 NOE ( Fig. 3 ) as well as the observed J
15 α –20
coupling value of 11.0 Hz, which requires the H-20 α /H-15 α dihedral angle to be ~0 ◦ (
). The 19 R configuration was assigned based on the chemical shifts of H-18 ( δ H 1.27), H-19 ( δ H 3.88), H-21 ( δ H 4.18), and C-21 resonance ( δ C 54.7), which correspond to those of the 19 R series of iboga alkaloids with a β -substituted hydroxyethyl side chain at C-20 (
;
;
). The 19 R configuration was further confirmed by the Gauge-Including Atomic Orbital (GIAO) NMR calculations and DP4+ probability analysis (
). The experimental NMR data were compared with the calculated 1 H and 13 C NMR shifts of 3 and its C-19 epimer 3a , using DP4+ probability analysis. As shown in Fig. 7 , compound 3 with 19 R configuration showed DP4+probability score of 100% (based on all NMR data). Finally, the absolute configuration of 3 was established as (3 S , 14 R , 16 S , 19 R , 20 S , 21 S ) based on comparison of the experimental and calculated ECD spectra ( Fig. 4 ).

A plausible biosynthetic pathway to 3 , 4 , and 5 from an iboga precursor, 3( S )-cyanocoronaridine ( 15 ) (
) is shown in Fig. 8 . Hydrolysis of 15 followed by reduction leads to ervatamine G ( 16 ) (
). Subsequent formation of the enamine 17 , followed by an intermolecular enamine-formaldehyde reaction leads to the C-25 hydroxy intermediate, 18 . Finally, oxidation of 18 leads to 5 . Compounds 3 and 4 may have formed from a similar biosynthetic pathway with the hypothetical 19 R -hydroxy derivative of 3 ( S )-cyanocoronaridine 19 .

Polyneurine G ( 7 )
was isolated as an orange oil, [α] D 25 25 ( c 0.4, CHCl 3 ). The UV spectrum showed absorption maxima indicative of an indole chromophore at 225, 285, and 293 nm , while the IR spectrum showed the presence of NH/OH and ester groups at 3376 and
1728 cm 1 , respectively. The HRESIMS data ([M + H] + m/z 371.1984) established the molecular formula of 7 as C 21 H 26 N 2 O 4 . The 1 H NMR data ( Table 1 ) showed the presence of an indolic NH ( δ H 8.13), four aromatic hydrogens ( δ H 7.08–7.47), a methyl ester ( δ H 3.73), and a 1,2-disubstituted ethyl side chain ( δ H 3.61, 3.76, H-18; δ H 3.78, H-19). The 13 C NMR data ( Table 2 ) indicated 21 carbon resonances, comprising six methylenes, eight methines, one methyl ester, one ester carbonyl, two tertiary carbons linked to indolic NH, and three quaternary carbons. The COSY and HMBC data ( Fig. 2 ) led to the elucidation of the structure for the compound as the vicinally-dihydroxysubstituted coronaridine derivative (18,19-dihydroxycoronaridine). The oxymethylene and oxymethine resonances corresponding to the vicinally-dihydroxysubstituted C-18 C-19 were seen at δ C 65.8 and 75.5, respectively. A search of the literature revealed that this 2D structure was previously assigned to 18,19-dihydroxycoronaridine ( 20 ) (
), which does not possess identical 1 H and 13 C NMR data to those of 7 , suggesting 7 to be an epimer of 20 . Since the relative configurations at C-14, C-16, C-20, and C-21 were found to be identical to those of compounds 1–6 ( Fig. 3 ), the only stereochemical difference between compounds 7 and 20 must be at C-19. The stereochemistry at C-19 was assigned by comparing the 13 C NMR data of 7 and 20 with those of 19 R - and 19 S -heyneanine (
;
). In 7 , C- 15 and C-21 were observed at δ C 28.3 and δ C 54.9, respectively, which correspond to the corresponding carbon shifts in the 19 R -hydroxyiboga alkaloid series such as 19- epi -heyneanine (i.e., C-15 at ca. δ C 29; C-21 at ca. δ C 55). On the contrary, C-15 and C-21 of 20 were found at δ C 23.7 and δ C 59.2, respectively (
), which are consistent with those found in the 19 S -hydroxyiboga alkaloid series such as heyneanine. We can therefore deduce that compound 7 possesses an opposite relative configuration at C-19 (i.e., S ), compared to 20 with a 19 R configuration (
). The deduction was further confirmed by GIAO NMR calculations and DP4+ analysis. The experimental NMR data were compared with the calculated 1 H and 13 C NMR shifts of 7 and its C-19 epimer 7a using DP4+analysis. The DP4+results supported 7 with 19 S configuration as the correct relative configuration, with 100% DP4+ probability (all data) ( Fig. 7 ). Finally, the absolute configuration of 7 was established as (14 R , 16 S , 19 S , 20 S , 21 S ) based on comparison of the experimental and calculated ECD spectra ( Fig. 4 ). Compound 7 is thus identified as 18,19( S )-dihydroxycoronaridine.

Polyneurine H ( 8 )
was obtained as a yellowish oil, [α] D 25 30 ( c 0.1, CHCl 3 ). The UV spectrum exhibited absorption maxima indicative of a hydroxyindolenine chromophore at 223, 232 sh, 266, and 292 nm , while the IR spectrum showed the presence of OH and ester carbonyl groups at 3301 and
1732 cm
1 , respectively. The HRESIMS data ([M + H] + m/z 371.1962) established the molecular formula of 8 as C 21 H 26 N 2 O 4 . The 1 H and 13 C NMR data ( Tables 1 and 2 ) revealed the presence of four aromatic resonances of an unsubstituted indole moiety ( δ H 7.25–7.48), a methyl ester group ( δ H 3.71; δ C 53.4, 172.9), a hydroxyethyl side chain ( δ H 1.24, 3.85; δ C 22.2, 70.3), and a broad singlet at δ H 3.26 due to an OH group (confirmed by D 2 O exchange experiment). The imine function in 8 was readily identified from the characteristic C-2 resonance observed at δ C 188.6, in
addition to the absence of an indolic NH signal in the 1 H NMR spectrum
.
The oxygenated tertiary carbon (C-7) associated with the hydroxyindolenine was clearly observed at δ C 88.0. Examination of the COSY and HMBC data ( Fig. 2 ) led to the structure as shown in 8 . A search of the literature revealed that this 2D structure was previously assigned to heyneanine hydroxyindolenine ( 21 ) (
;
), which does not have identical NMR data to those of 8 , suggesting 8 to be a diastereomer of 21 . Since the relative configurations at C-14, C-16, C-20, and C-21 were established to be the same as those of compounds 1–7 ( Fig. 3 ), the stereochemical differences between compounds 8 and 21 must be at C-7 and/or C-19. As with compounds 3 , 4 , and 7 , the C-19 configuration of 8 was readily determined as R from the observed carbon shifts of C-15 ( δ C 28.5) and C-21 ( δ C 54.2), which correspond to those of the 19 R -hydroxyiboga alkaloid series ( vide supra ) such as 19- epi -heyneanine (C-15 at ca. δ C 29 and C-21 at ca. δ C 55) (
;
). The 19 R configuration was also supported by the GIAO NMR calculations and DP4+ analysis of 8 , which showed 100% probability (all data) ( Fig. 7 ). The configuration at C-7 was assigned as S based on the NOE interaction observed between H-21 and 7-OH ( Fig. 3 ). Finally, the absolute configuration of 8 was established as (7 S , 14 R , 16 S , 19 R , 20 S , 21 S ) based on comparison of the experimental and calculated ECD spectra ( Fig. 4 ). Compound 8 is therefore the 7 S , 19 R diastereomer of 7 R , 19 S -heyneanine hydroxyindolenine
(
21
).

The present study on the bark of 

Tabernaemontana polyneura

afforded eight previously undescribed iboga alkaloids (
1–8
). The structures of these compounds were established by interpretation of the MS and NMR data, GIAO NMR calculations and DP4+ probability analysis, TDDFT-ECD method, or X-ray diffraction analysis. A previous study of the same plant from a different location found only four new alkaloids in the stem bark extract, viz., two vobasine and two iboga alkaloids (

). The present study has resulted in the isolation of eight additional previously undescribed iboga alkaloids.

Conformational searches were performed by Spartan’14 software (

) using the MMFF94 force field. Conformers occurring within a 5 kcal mol 
1
energy window from the global minima were then imported into the Gaussian 09 software (

) for geometry optimization and frequency calculation at DFT level using the B3LYP functional with a basis set of 6–31G(d). TDDFT ECD calculations were performed on the optimized conformers at the B3LYP or 
ω
B97X-D/6-311G++(d,p) level using a PCM solvation model for MeOH. The ECD spectrum for each optimized conformer was weighted by Boltzmann distribution, and the overall ECD curves were produced by SpecDis (version 1.64) software (

) after UV correction. Gauge-Including Atomic Orbital (GIAO) NMR calculations were performed on the optimized conformers at the mPW1PW91/6-31 +G (d,p) level with PCM solvation model for CHCl 
3
. The Boltzmann-averaged magnetic shielding tensors were converted into chemical shifts (ppm) with TMS as the reference standard (

; 

). The DP4+ calculations were carried out using the Excel spreadsheet provided by the Sarotti group (

).
